            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marcus Hayes\u2019s story is woven from the cultural threads of the Bay Area. Born and raised in West Oakland, he was the son of a high school English teacher and a union longshoreman. His childhood was a blend of his mother\u2019s passion for literature and community arts projects and his father\u2019s steadfast belief in collective action and public service. This foundation shaped his worldview, instilling in him a deep appreciation for culture as a cornerstone of community well-being.\n\nHis educational journey was purposeful. After earning a B.A. in Sociology from UC Berkeley, where he focused on urban communities, he felt a pull toward public administration. He wanted to be on the inside, shaping the policies that could either nurture or neglect the cultural ecosystems he valued. This led him to a Master of Public Administration degree from the University of San Francisco, cementing his connection to the city across the bay.\n\nHis career began with an entry-level analyst position at City Hall. Though tedious, the role taught him the intricate mechanics of municipal bureaucracy. A turning point came when he was assigned to a task force evaluating funding for community arts programs. He fought passionately to save a beloved mural project in the Mission District from budget cuts, successfully navigating stakeholder meetings and crafting a compelling case for its public value. This victory was a revelation; he had found his calling at the intersection of public policy and artistic expression. He soon joined the San Francisco Arts Commission, working his way up to Program Director through diligence and an unwavering commitment to equitable arts funding.\n\nToday, Marcus lives in a cozy Duboce Triangle apartment with his partner of eight years, David, a graphic designer. His daily routine begins with the N Judah Muni line, a 3.8-mile journey to his office at the War Memorial Veterans Building that he uses for reading and reflection. His days are a whirlwind of grant reviews, community outreach meetings, and strategic planning. Marcus is a fixture in his neighborhood, known at his local coffee shop and a regular at the farmers' market. His aspiration isn't for higher office but for legacy: to establish a permanent, fully-funded endowment for public art in San Francisco, ensuring that the city's creative soul is protected for generations to come."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the chalky smell of primer and the rumble of I-880 overhead. He was nine, helping his mother outline a community mural on a concrete support pillar in West Oakland. His job was to stir the thick, sky-blue paint. He watched neighbors stop and smile, adding their own small touches. It wasn't just art; it was a barn raising. That day, he learned that culture wasn\u2019t something you hang in a museum\u2014it was something you build together, with your own hands, to make a piece of the world feel like home.\n\n2.\nThe moment wasn\u2019t his passionate speech, but the silence after. He stood at the back of the conference room at City Hall, a young analyst who\u2019d just convinced the committee not to defund the Mission mural project. An elderly artist with paint-flecked hands silently gripped his shoulder. In that quiet gesture, Marcus felt the weight and worth of his work for the first time. He wasn't just pushing paper; he was protecting a piece of the city\u2019s soul. His parents\u2019 lessons\u2014art and action\u2014had finally clicked into place.\n\n3.\nIt was their third date. Marcus nervously took David to see the Clarion Alley murals, terrified his world of public art would seem... bureaucratic. But David, a graphic designer, didn't just see paintings; he saw typography, color theory, and political courage. \"This is the city's real voice,\" David said, squeezing his hand. In that moment, Marcus felt seen, personally and professionally. His life\u2019s passion wasn\u2019t just a job he had to explain; it was something he could share with the person he was beginning to love.\n\n4.\nAfter securing a major grant for youth arts programs, he called his father. He expected a simple \"congratulations.\" Instead, his dad, the longshoreman, said, \"Fighting for people's contracts, fighting for their art... it's the same fight, son. It's for dignity.\" Marcus felt a profound click of understanding. The union hall and the art gallery weren't so far apart. His work wasn\u2019t a departure from his father's world but a continuation of it, ensuring the community had not only bread, but roses too.\n\n5.\nMost mornings on the N Judah are for reading, but some are just for watching. He recalls one foggy morning, emerging from the Sunset Tunnel, when the sun broke through and illuminated the Victorian homes of Duboce Triangle. The whole world went from gray to gold. It was a simple, fleeting image of the city he worked for. The moment reaffirmed his entire purpose: to protect and foster the beauty, big and small, that makes a city worth loving, for every single person on that train."
